{"title_page": "Crozant", "text_new": "{{short description|Commune in Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France}}\n{{Infobox French commune\n|name                   = Crozant\n|commune status         = [[Communes of France|Commune]]\n|image                  = France Summer 2008 038.JPG\n|caption                = The church in Crozant\n|image coat of arms     = \n|arrondissement         = Gu\u00e9ret\n|canton                 = Dun-le-Palestel\n|INSEE                  = 23070\n|postal code            = 23160\n|mayor                  = Jean Parlebas\n|term                   = 2008&ndash;2014\n|intercommunality       = [[Communaut\u00e9 de communes du Pays Dunois|CC Pays Dunois]]\n|coordinates            = {{coord|46.3925|1.6222|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation m            = 277\n|area km2               = 31.9\n|population             = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_total}}\n|population date        = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_as_of}}\n|population footnotes   = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_footnotes}}\n}}\n\n'''Crozant''' is a [[Communes of France|commune]] in the [[Creuse]] [[Departments of France|department]] in the [[Nouvelle-Aquitaine]] [[Regions of France|region]] in [[France]].\n\n==Geography==\nA tourism and farming village situated some {{convert|20|mi|km}} northeast of Gu\u00e9ret, on the D72 and by the banks of the river [[Creuse River|Creuse]], the boundary with the department of [[Indre]].\n\nThis administrative boundary is very old. It approximates to the linguistic boundary between the [[langue d'o\u00efl]] and [[langue d'oc]].\n\nIt also has a geological significance: to the south, the granite foothills of the [[Massif central]], while in the plains to the north begins the limestone of the Paris basin. <br>\nWhen the [[Eguzon dam]] on the Creuse was built in 1926, the landscape, society and the local economy changed under the water\u2019s influence in just a few years. One has only to see old postcards and the works of [[Armand Guillaumin]], who painted about 140 landscapes, to notice the difference. The moors were maintained by the extensive grazing of sheep and goats, which slowly declined between the two wars and died out completely after 1950. The trend nowadays is the restoration of surrounding ruins, and the forestation of those former natural open spaces.\n[[Image:La Creuse \u00e0 Crozant (Fr).jpg|thumb|left|Creuse river]]\n\n==Population==\n{{Historical populations\n|align=left\n|1962|909\n|1968|929\n|1975|862\n|1982|732\n|1990|636\n|1999|581\n|2008|511\n}}\n{{clear-left}}\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Creuse - Ch\u00e2teau Crozant.jpg|thumb|left|Ruins of the ch\u00e2teau]]\nThe name of Crozant is probably derived from [[Celtic languages|Celtic]] then the [[Latin]] \"Croso\" (which also gives us \"Creuse\"). The Welsh word \"Croeso\" means welcome and as the Welsh are Celts I suspect that there is a link. Successively known as ''Crozenc'' in 1208, Crozent in 1277, Crousant (1512) and the modern form \"Crozant\". <br>\nThe rocky outcrop between the [[Creuse River|Creuse]] and its tributary, the S\u00e9delle has been occupied since prehistoric times. A fortress appears to have been built between 997 and 1018. But it was in the 13th century that the castle we know today was built. One of the remaining towers bears the name of [[Isabella of Angoul\u00eame]], widow of [[King John I of England]], subsequently the wife of Hugues X de Lusignan.<br>\nIn his book on the history of the region ([[County of La Marche|La Marche]]), Joullietton reported that the castle at Crozant was taken by Catholics in 1588, which ruined one of the towers. From 1606, the castle served as a source of building material for the local people. Notes prepared in 1640, by the king\u2019s inspector at [[Moulins, Allier|Moulins]], Voyer d'Argenson, noted that the castle was in a sad state. The remains of the stronghold, which had belonged to the Crown since the confiscation of all the property of [[Charles III, Duke of Bourbon]], [[Constable of France]] in 1527, was then acquired by Gabriel Beaupr\u00e9, governor of [[County of La Marche|La Marche]]. <br>\nThe ruins of the citadel cover a large part of the spur, with several successive ramparts, a square 15th-century [[donjon]] and two 13th-century towers plus a chapel and a \"tour de l\u2019eau\u2019\u2019 from where water could be raised from the river whilst covered and safe from attack.<br>\nAt the end of lengthy negotiations led by the mayor of Crozant, the ruins were acquired a few years ago by the commune. A major reconstruction programme was undertaken, with funding from the state, regional and local councils, resulting in the reopening of the site to the public (\u20ac2 adults - \u20ac1.50 concessions (2008)).\n\nFrom the nineteenth century, the area around Crozant inspired many painters. Perhaps the first was Paul Castans (1823\u20131892), who inspired [[Armand Guillaumin]] (1841\u20131927), to choose Crozant as his residence of choice. They give birth to the [[Crozant School]] (in French, L'Ecole de Crozant), for all those who found inspiration by the shores of the Creuse. Among them were: Pierre Ballue (1855-1928), Ernest Josephson (1851\u20131906), [[Alfred Smith (artist)|Alfred Smith]] (1854 - 1932), Fernand Maillaud (1862\u20131948), Paul Madeline, Clementine Ballot (1880\u20131924), the Leloir dynasty (particularly Mauritius Leloir (1853\u20131940)), Swede Walter Oetten ( 1897\u20131972), Solange Christauflour (1900\u20131953), Ernest Victor Hareux and so on. Not far from the church there is a bronze bust of Guillaumin.\nIn 1926, the demand for electricity generation led to the creation of the [[Eguzon dam]]. This created a new tourist attraction known as Lake Chambon after the hamlet bordering [[\u00c9guzon]]. The painters\u2019 landscapes now included the lake, which also has boats for hire and dinner cruises around it.\n\n<gallery mode=\"nolines\" class=\"center\" heights=\"250\" widths=\"250\" >\nFile:Lille PdBA castan soiree octobre.JPG|''Soir\u00e9e d'octobre'', by Gustave Eug\u00e8ne Castan (1864).\nFile:MuMA - Guillaumin - Paysage de neige \u00e0 Crozant.JPG|''Paysage de neige \u00e0 Crozant'' (''Snow at Crozant''), by [[Armand Guillaumin]] (1895).\nFile:Smith Alfred - Crozant La S\u00e9delle en octobre (c 1923).jpg|''La S\u00e9delle en octobre'', by [[Alfred Smith (artist)|Alfred Smith]] (c. 1923.]\n</gallery>\n\nDuring the [[Second World War]], the bridge separating the Creuse from [[Indre]] at Crozant was dynamited. A temporary [[pontoon bridge]] was installed pending the construction of the new bridge. Today, when the water level is low enough, one can still see a stone stack of the old bridge lying on its side.\n\n==Sights==\n* The church of St. Etienne, dating from the twelfth century.\n* The ruins of the 11th-century castle of Crozant, currently undergoing considerable restoration.\n* The remains of the 15th-century ch\u00e2teau des Places.\n* The chapel of St. Madeleine dating from the seventeenth century.\n* The gardens and [[Arboretum de la S\u00e9delle]].\n\n==Personalities==\n* [[Gilles Cl\u00e9ment]], gardener and botanist.\n* [[Armand Guillaumin]], painter.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Communes of the Creuse department]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Crozant}}\n* [http://www.quid.fr/communes.html?mode=detail&id=20115&req=Crozant Crozant on the Quid website]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} {{in lang|fr}}\n* [http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=INSEE&VALUE_1=23070 Crozant entries in the Ministry of Culture website]\n* [http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/memoire_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_5=LBASE&VALUE_5=PA00100050 Ministry of Culture pictures of the castle]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090422161855/http://www.jedecouvrelafrance.com/f-1008.creuse-forteresse-de-crozant.html Ch\u00e2teau de Crozant website]\n\n{{Creuse communes}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communes of Creuse]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Commune in Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France}}\n{{Infobox French commune\n|name                   = Crozant\n|commune status         = [[Communes of France|Commune]]\n|image                  = France Summer 2008 038.JPG\n|caption                = The church in Crozant\n|image coat of arms     = \n|arrondissement         = Gu\u00e9ret\n|canton                 = Dun-le-Palestel\n|INSEE                  = 23070\n|postal code            = 23160\n|mayor                  = Jean Parlebas\n|term                   = 2008&ndash;2014\n|intercommunality       = [[Communaut\u00e9 de communes du Pays Dunois|CC Pays Dunois]]\n|coordinates            = {{coord|46.3925|1.6222|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation m            = 277\n|area km2               = 31.9\n|population             = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_total}}\n|population date        = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_as_of}}\n|population footnotes   = {{France metadata Wikidata|population_footnotes}}\n}}\n\n'''Crozant''' is a [[Communes of France|commune]] in the [[Creuse]] [[Departments of France|department]] in the [[Nouvelle-Aquitaine]] [[Regions of France|region]] in [[France]].\n\n==Geography==\nA tourism and farming village situated some {{convert|20|mi|km}} northeast of Gu\u00e9ret, on the D72 and by the banks of the river [[Creuse River|Creuse]], the boundary with the department of [[Indre]].\n\nThis administrative boundary is very old. It approximates to the linguistic boundary between the [[langue d'o\u00efl]] and [[langue d'oc]].\n\nIt also has a geological significance: to the south, the granite foothills of the [[Massif central]], while in the plains to the north begins the limestone of the Paris basin. <br>\nWhen the [[Eguzon dam]] on the Creuse was built in 1926, the landscape, society and the local economy changed under the water\u2019s influence in just a few years. One has only to see old postcards and the works of [[Armand Guillaumin]], who painted about 140 landscapes, to notice the difference. The moors were maintained by the extensive grazing of sheep and goats, which slowly declined between the two wars and died out completely after 1950. The trend nowadays is the restoration of surrounding ruins, and the forestation of those former natural open spaces.\n[[Image:La Creuse \u00e0 Crozant (Fr).jpg|thumb|left|Creuse river]]\n\n==Population==\n{{Historical populations\n|align=left\n|1962|909\n|1968|929\n|1975|862\n|1982|732\n|1990|636\n|1999|581\n|2008|511\n}}\n{{clear-left}}\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Creuse - Ch\u00e2teau Crozant.jpg|thumb|left|Ruins of the ch\u00e2teau]]\nThe name of Crozant is probably derived from [[Celtic languages|Celtic]] then the [[Latin]] \"Croso\" (which also gives us \"Creuse\"). The Welsh word \"Croeso\" means welcome and as the Welsh are Celts I suspect that there is a link. Successively known as ''Crozenc'' in 1208, Crozent in 1277, Crousant (1512) and the modern form \"Crozant\". <br>\nThe rocky outcrop between the [[Creuse River|Creuse]] and its tributary, the S\u00e9delle has been occupied since prehistoric times. A fortress appears to have been built between 997 and 1018. But it was in the 13th century that the castle we know today was built. One of the remaining towers bears the name of [[Isabella of Angoul\u00eame]], widow of [[King John I of England]], subsequently the wife of Hugues X de Lusignan.<br>\nIn his book on the history of the region ([[County of La Marche|La Marche]]), Joullietton reported that the castle at Crozant was taken by Catholics in 1588, which ruined one of the towers. From 1606, the castle served as a source of building material for the local people. Notes prepared in 1640, by the king\u2019s inspector at [[Moulins, Allier|Moulins]], Voyer d'Argenson, noted that the castle was in a sad state. The remains of the stronghold, which had belonged to the Crown since the confiscation of all the property of [[Charles III, Duke of Bourbon]], [[Constable of France]] in 1527, was then acquired by Gabriel Beaupr\u00e9, governor of [[County of La Marche|La Marche]]. <br>\nThe ruins of the citadel cover a large part of the spur, with several successive ramparts, a square 15th-century [[donjon]] and two 13th-century towers plus a chapel and a \"tour de l\u2019eau\u2019\u2019 from where water could be raised from the river whilst covered and safe from attack.<br>\nAt the end of lengthy negotiations led by the mayor of Crozant, the ruins were acquired a few years ago by the commune. A major reconstruction programme was undertaken, with funding from the state, regional and local councils, resulting in the reopening of the site to the public (\u20ac2 adults - \u20ac1.50 concessions (2008)).\n\n[[File:MuMA - Guillaumin - Paysage de neige \u00e0 Crozant.JPG|thumb|''Paysage de neige \u00e0 Crozant'' (''Snow at Crozant''), by Armand Guillaumin (1895).]]\nFrom the nineteenth century, the area around Crozant inspired many painters. Perhaps the first was Paul Castans (1823\u20131892), who inspired [[Armand Guillaumin]] (1841\u20131927), to choose Crozant as his residence of choice. They give birth to the [[Crozant School]] (in French, L'Ecole de Crozant), for all those who found inspiration by the shores of the Creuse. Among them were: Pierre Ballue (1855-1928), Ernest Josephson (1851\u20131906), [[Alfred Smith (artist)|Alfred Smith]] (1854 - 1932), Fernand Maillaud (1862\u20131948), Paul Madeline, Clementine Ballot (1880\u20131924), the Leloir dynasty (particularly Mauritius Leloir (1853\u20131940)), Swede Walter Oetten ( 1897\u20131972), Solange Christauflour (1900\u20131953), Ernest Victor Hareux and so on. Not far from the church there is a bronze bust of Guillaumin.\nIn 1926, the demand for electricity generation led to the creation of the [[Eguzon dam]]. This created a new tourist attraction known as Lake Chambon after the hamlet bordering [[\u00c9guzon]]. The painters\u2019 landscapes now included the lake, which also has boats for hire and dinner cruises around it.\nDuring the [[Second World War]], the bridge separating the Creuse from [[Indre]] at Crozant was dynamited. A temporary [[pontoon bridge]] was installed pending the construction of the new bridge. Today, when the water level is low enough, one can still see a stone stack of the old bridge lying on its side.\n\n==Sights==\n* The church of St. Etienne, dating from the twelfth century.\n* The ruins of the 11th-century castle of Crozant, currently undergoing considerable restoration.\n* The remains of the 15th-century ch\u00e2teau des Places.\n* The chapel of St. Madeleine dating from the seventeenth century.\n* The gardens and [[Arboretum de la S\u00e9delle]].\n\n==Personalities==\n* [[Gilles Cl\u00e9ment]], gardener and botanist.\n* [[Armand Guillaumin]], painter.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Communes of the Creuse department]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Crozant}}\n* [http://www.quid.fr/communes.html?mode=detail&id=20115&req=Crozant Crozant on the Quid website]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} {{in lang|fr}}\n* [http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=INSEE&VALUE_1=23070 Crozant entries in the Ministry of Culture website]\n* [http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/memoire_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_5=LBASE&VALUE_5=PA00100050 Ministry of Culture pictures of the castle]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090422161855/http://www.jedecouvrelafrance.com/f-1008.creuse-forteresse-de-crozant.html Ch\u00e2teau de Crozant website]\n\n{{Creuse communes}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communes of Creuse]]\n", "name_user": "Jefunky", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crozant"}
{"title_page": "Intellectual Ventures", "text_new": "{{Bias|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Intellectual Ventures Management, LLC\n| logo             =Intellectual_Ventures_logo.png\n| type             = [[Privately held company]]\n| predecessor      =\n| successor        =\n| founder          = [[Nathan Myhrvold]]<br>Edward Jung<br>[[Peter Detkin]]<br>Gregory Gorder\n| defunct          =\n| fate             =\n| area_served      =\n| key_people       =\n| industry         = [[Patent monetization]]\n| products         =\n| services         =\n| revenue          =\n| operating_income =\n| net_income       =\n| aum              =\n| assets           =\n| equity           =\n| owner            =\n| num_employees    = 800\n| parent           =\n| divisions        =\n| subsid           =\n| footnotes        =\n| intl             =\n| homepage         = [http://www.intellectualventures.com/ www.intellectualventures.com]\n| foundation       =\n| location_city    = [[Bellevue, Washington]]\n| location_country = [[United States]]\n| location         =\n| locations        = 10\n| market cap       =\n}}\n\n'''Intellectual Ventures''' is an American private company that centers on the development and licensing of intellectual property.  Intellectual Ventures is one of the top-five owners of U.S. patents, as of 2011.<ref>[http://www.patentlyo.com/patent/2011/05/intellectual-ventures-revealing-investors.html \"Intellectual Ventures: Revealing Investors \"], [[Patently-O]] blog, May 18, 2011. Consulted on May 21, 2011.</ref> {{Verify source|date=June 2017}} Its business model has a focus on buying patents and aggregating them into a large [[patent portfolio]] and licensing these patents to third parties. The company has been described as the country's largest and most notorious [[patent trolling]] company,<ref>{{cite web |title=RPX and the complicated business of stockpiling patents for good, not evil |url=https://pando.com/2013/09/09/rpx-and-the-complicated-business-of-stockpiling-patents-for-good-not-evil/ |website=Pando |language=en-gb |date=9 September 2013}}</ref> the ultimate [[patent troll]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Robertson |first1=Adi |title=The ultimate patent troll is going to trial against Google and Motorola |url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/2/4/5375304/intellectual-ventures-goes-to-trial-against-google-and-motorola |website=The Verge |date=4 February 2014}}</ref>, and the most hated company in tech.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kerstetter |first1=Jim |title=Inside Intellectual Ventures, the most hated company in tech |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/inside-intellectual-ventures-the-most-hated-company-in-tech/ |website=CNET |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the firm launched a prototyping and research laboratory,  Intellectual Ventures Lab''','''<ref>[http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2009266390_intvent70.html \"Bellevue lab is an inventor's real dream\"] by Brier Dudley, The Seattle Times -  27 May 2009<!--accessed June 1, 2009--></ref> which attracted media controversy when the book ''[[SuperFreakonomics]]'' described its ideas for [[Climate change mitigation|reducing global climate change]]. The firm also collaborates on humanitarian projects through its Global Good program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.intellectualventures.com/globalgood/|title=Global Good|website=www.intellectualventures.com|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nIn 2000, Intellectual Ventures was founded as a private partnership by [[Nathan Myhrvold]] and Edward Jung of [[Microsoft]], later joined by co-founders [[Peter Detkin]] of [[Intel]], and Gregory Gorder of [[Perkins Coie]].  The Intellectual Ventures Management Company is owned 40% [[Nathan Myhrvold]], 20% [[Peter Detkin]], 20% Gregory Gorder and 20% Edward Jung. They reportedly have raised over $5.5 billion from many large companies including [[Microsoft]], [[Intel]], [[Sony]], [[Nokia]], [[Apple Computer|Apple]], [[Google]], [[Yahoo]], [[American Express]], [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]], [[SAP AG|SAP]], [[Nvidia]], and [[eBay]], plus investment firms such as [[Stanford]], [[Hewlett Foundation]], [[Mayo Clinic]], and [[Charles River Ventures]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patentlyo.com/financial-interest-in-iv.pdf|title=Defendants Certificate of Interest|date=2011-05-16|publisher=US District Court, N. California|access-date=2013-07-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006095916/http://www.patentlyo.com/financial-interest-in-iv.pdf|archive-date=2012-10-06|url-status=dead}}</ref> In December 2013, the firm released a list of approximately 33,000 of the nearly 40,000 assets in their monetization program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://patents.intven.com/finder|title=Intellectual Ventures Find a Patent|date=2013-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richardsonoliver.com/news/2014/6/4/whats-inside-ivs-patent-portfolio|title=What's Inside IV's Patent Portfolio|location=London| work=[[IAM Magazine]]|first=Kent|last=Richardson|date=2014-06-14}} Issue 66. July/August 2014</ref> Licenses to patents are obtained through investment and [[royalties]].<ref>[http://www.pcworld.com/article/id,132174-c,opensource/article.html \"Ubuntu: Microsoft is Patent Pal\"] by Matthew Broersma, PCWorld - 23 May 2007</ref> In March 2009, the firm announced expansion into China, India, Japan, Korea and Singapore to build partnerships with  scientists and institutions in Asia.\n<!--\nNotable then uncomment?: In November 2015, Intellectual Ventures opened a new lab<ref>http://www.intellectualventures.com/insights/archives/intellectual-ventures-opens-new-laboratory</ref> -->\n\n==Investment funds==\nThe company operates three primary investment funds:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.intellectualventures.com/Libraries/General/Investing_in_Invention_Graphical_Representation.sflb.ashx |title=Investing in Invention |accessdate=2010-12-26 |website=Intellectual Ventures |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100630210845/http://www.intellectualventures.com/Libraries/General/Investing_in_Invention_Graphical_Representation.sflb.ashx |archivedate=2010-06-30 }}</ref>\n\n* Invention Investment Fund (IIF), purchasing existing inventions and licensing them\n* Invention Development Fund (IDF), partnering chiefly with research institutions to file descriptions of new inventions\n* Investment Science Fund (ISF), focused on internally developed inventions\n\n==Intellectual Ventures Lab==\nIn 2009, Intellectual Ventures launched a prototyping and research laboratory,  Intellectual Ventures Lab, hiring  scientists to imagine inventions which could exist but do not yet exist, and then filing descriptions of these inventions with the US Patent Office.  Notable participants  include [[Robert Langer]] of MIT, [[Leroy Hood]] of the [[Institute for Systems Biology]], Ed Harlow of Harvard Medical School, [[Bran Ferren]] and [[Danny Hillis]] of [[Applied Minds]], and Sir [[John Pendry]] of Imperial College.{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}}  The ''[[Sunday Times]]'' reported that the company applies for about 450 patents per year, in areas from vaccine research to optical computing and, as of May 2010, 91 of the applications had been approved.<ref name=\"Harris\">{{cite news |url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/entrepreneur/article7127608.ece\n|title=Green Pioneers: Godfather of nutty inventions\n| location=London\n| work=[[The Times]]\n| first=Mark\n| last=Harris\n| date=May 16, 2010\n}} Mark Harris, The Sunday Times, May 16, 2010</ref> Internally developed inventions include a [[Traveling wave reactor|safer nuclear reactor design]] (which won the MIT Technology Review Top 10 Emerging Technologies in 2009) that can use uranium waste as fuel or thorium which is plentiful and poses no proliferation risk,<ref>[http://beta.technologyreview.com/read_article.aspx?ch=specialsections&sc=tr10&id=22114 \"TR10: Traveling-Wave Reactor\"]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} by Matt Wald, Technology Review - March/April 2009</ref> a mosquito-targeting laser,<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/science/article5908535.ece \"Mosquito laser gun offers new hope on malaria\"] by Tony Allen-Mills - 15 March 2009</ref> and a series of computer models of infectious disease.<ref>[http://www.hertzfoundation.org/lib/literature/Hertz_Spring09_V11.pdf \"Mathematics, Mosquitoes, and Malaria\"] by Philip Eckhoff, Hertz Foundation Biennial Symposium - Spring 2009, Volume 11</ref>\n\nTheir efforts to promote a method to reverse or reduce the effects of global climate change by artificially recreating the conditions from the aftermath of a volcanic eruption gained media coverage following the release of the book ''SuperFreakonomics'', whose chapter about [[global warming]] proposes that the global climate can be regulated by [[geo-engineering]] of a [[stratoshield]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://intellectualventureslab.com/?tag=stratoshield|title=Introducing the Stratoshield|date=2009-10-21|publisher=Intellectual Ventures}}</ref> based upon patented technology from the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.techflash.com/seattle/2009/10/video_nathan_myhrvold_explains_how_to_save_the_world.html|title=Stratoshield: Nathan Myhrvold explains how to save the planet|author=Todd Bishop|publisher=TechFlash|date=2009-10-14}}</ref> The chapter has been criticized by some economists and climate science experts who say it contains numerous misleading statements and discredited arguments, including this presentation of geoengineering as a replacement for CO<sub>2</sub> emissions reduction.  Among the critics are [[Paul Krugman]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/10/17/superfreakonomics-on-climate-part-1/ |title=SuperFreakonomics on climate, part 1 |author=Paul Krugman |date=2009-10-17 |quote=\"they grossly misrepresent other peoples\u2019 research, in both climate science and economics\" | work=The New York Times}}</ref> [[J. Bradford DeLong|Brad DeLong]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://delong.typepad.com/sdj/2009/10/yet-more-superfreakonomics-blogging-yes-i-know-i-know.html |title=Yet More SuperFreakonomics Blogging. |author=Brad DeLong |date=2009-10-19 |work=Grasping Reality with All Eight Tentacles|quote=Levitt and Dubner today appear to no longer be thinking like economists}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2009/oct/19/superfreakonomics-geoengineering-wrong|title=Why SuperFreakonomics' authors are wrong on geo-engineering|date=2009-10-19|quote=Many commentators have already pointed out dozens of misquotes, misrepresentations and mistakes in the 'Global Cooling' chapter | location=London | work=The Guardian}}</ref> and ''[[The Economist]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/world/international/displaystory.cfm?story_id=14738383|title=Freaking out: The controversy over SuperFreakonomics |date=2009-10-27|publisher=The Economist|accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref>  Elizabeth Kolbert, a science writer for ''[[The New Yorker]]'' who has written extensively on global warming, contends that \"just about everything they [Levitt and Dubner] have to say on the topic is, factually speaking, wrong.\"<ref>\"{{cite news |author=Kolbert, Elizabeth |title=Hosed: Is there a quick fix for the climate?\" [rev. of Levitt and Dubner's SuperFreakonomics and Al Gore's Our Choice] |url=http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/books/2009/11/16/091116crbo_books_kolbert |publisher=New Yorker |date=November 16, 2009  }}</ref> In response, Levitt and Dubner have stated on their ''Freakonomics'' blog that global warming is [[Human impact on the environment|man-made]] and an important issue. They warn against claims of an inevitable doomsday; instead they look to raise awareness of less traditional or popular, methods to tackle the potential problem of global warming.<ref>{{Cite news|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|url=http://freakonomics.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/10/17/the-rumors-of-our-global-warming-denial-are-greatly-exaggerated/|title=The Rumors of Our Global-Warming Denial Are Greatly Exaggerated|date=2009-10-17|quote=\"... we believe that rising global temperatures are a man-made phenomenon and that global warming is an important issue to solve. Where we differ from the critics is in our view of the most effective solutions to this problem.\" and \"The real purpose of the chapter is figuring out how to cool the Earth if indeed it becomes catastrophically warmer... if we weren\u2019t convinced that global warming was worth worrying about, we wouldn\u2019t have written a chapter about proposed solutions. | first=Steven D. | last=Levitt}}</ref>\n\n[[Lowell Wood]], an \"inventor in residence\" at Intellectual Ventures, became the most-patented inventor in US history in 2015, breaking the record held by Thomas Edison for over 80 years.\n\n== Global Good ==\nGlobal Good is collaboration between the firm and the Gates Foundation to develop  solutions for pressing problems in the developing world. It's technologies include:\n\nArktek, a passive vaccine storage device that allows [[vaccine]]s to be transported to parts of the world that lack reliable refrigeration. It uses a small amount of ice for cooling and requires no external power supply, relying on extraordinary insulation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2015/11/23/455580587/how-do-you-keep-vaccines-cool-try-spacecraft-insulation|title=How Do You Keep Vaccines Cool? Try Spacecraft Insulation|website=NPR.org|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref> The device has been used to transport vaccines around the world, and  Myhrvold believes the device may be useful for transporting organs. The firm produced a modified version of the Arktek to transport newly developed [[Ebola virus disease|Ebola]] vaccines to [[Sierra Leone]] and [[Guinea]] during the [[West African Ebola virus epidemic|2014 Ebola outbreak]] at the required much colder temperature.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/01/world/africa/experimental-ebola-vaccine-in-guinea-shows-promise-report-says.html|title=Experimental Ebola Vaccine Tested in Guinea Shows Promise, Report Says|last=Fink|first=Sheri|date=2015-07-31|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref>\n\nThe Photonic Fence is a device  to identify and kill mosquitos with lasers to prevent malaria, suggested by  Lowell Wood, an company researcher.   The device uses a non-lethal laser to track insects and monitor their wing-beat frequency. If it detects a female mosquito, the device fires a kill laser. It has an effective range of 100 feet and can purportedly kill up to 100 mosquitoes per second. The device has not yet been mass-produced,.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.geekwire.com/2015/intellectual-ventures-laser-mosquito-zapper-one-step-closer-to-commercialization/|title=Intellectual Ventures\u2019 laser mosquito zapper lands key licensing deal|date=2015-03-03|website=GeekWire|language=en-US|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref>\n\nThe Autoscope uses artificial intelligence to diagnose [[malaria]]. The device has been field-tested in Thailand and reportedly outperformed the average human diagnostician. It too is not yet scheduled for mass-production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/600779/artificial-intelligence-offers-a-better-way-to-diagnose-malaria/|title=Artificial Intelligence Offers a Better Way to Diagnose Malaria|website=MIT Technology Review|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref>\n\nMazzi is a milk jug designed for farmers in the developing world. The firm partnered with [[Heifer International]] to design the jug, which is cheap, sturdy, and easy to clean with features a funnel that results in decreased spillage.\n\n==Companies created==\nIntellectual Ventures has created a number of independent companies to bring its discoveries to mass market. Examples include [[Kymeta]], a satellite technology company,<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.kymetacorp.com/history/|title = Kymeta Company History|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151009170150/https://www.kymetacorp.com/history/|archive-date = 2015-10-09|url-status = dead}}</ref> [[TerraPower]], which seeks to improve nuclear power,<ref>{{Cite web|title = About TerraPower {{!}} TerraPower|url = http://terrapower.com/pages/about|website = terrapower.com|accessdate = 2015-11-01}}</ref> Evolv, which applies metamaterials to imaging,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.intellectualventures.com/inventions-patents/spinouts-programs/evolv/|title=Evolv|website=www.intellectualventures.com|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref> and [[Echodyne]], a [[metamaterial]]s-based radar communications company.<ref>{{Cite web|title = About Us {{!}} Echodyne|url = http://echodyne.com/about-us/|website = echodyne.com|accessdate = 2015-11-01}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n{{Main|Patent trolling}}\n\nPublicly, Intellectual Ventures states that a major goal is to assist small inventors against corporations. In practice, the vast majority of IV's revenue comes from buying patents, aggregating these patents into a single portfolio spanning many disparate technologies and [[Tying (commerce)|tying]] these patents together for license to other companies under the threat of litigation, or filing lawsuits for infringement of patents, a controversial practice referred to as \"patent trolling.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Here's Why Software Patents Are in Peril After the Intellectual Ventures Ruling |work=Fortune Magazine |url=http://fortune.com/2016/10/03/software-patents/ |first=Jeff John |last=Roberts |date=October 3, 2016 |accessdate=5 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIntellectual Ventures' purchased patents have largely been kept secret, though press releases with [[Telcordia]] and [[Transmeta]] indicated some or all of their patent portfolios were sold to the company. It reports that its purchasing activity as of spring 2010 has sent $350 million to individual inventors, and $848 million to small and medium size enterprises as well as returning \"approximately $1 billion\" to investors before filing any lawsuits, but IV's assistance to individual inventors has been contested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/441/when-patents-attack|title=When Patents Attack! {{!}} This American Life|website=This American Life|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref> Investigative journalism suggests that the company makes most of its income from lawsuits and licensing of already-existing inventions, rather than from its own innovation. Intellectual Ventures has been described as a \"patent troll\" by Shane Robison,<ref>{{cite journal |first=Nicholas |last=Varchaver |date=July 10, 2006 |title=Who's afraid of Nathan Myhrvold? |journal=Fortune |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2006/07/10/8380798/index.htm}}</ref> CTO of [[Hewlett Packard]] and others, allegedly accumulating patents not in order to develop products around them but with the goal to pressure large companies into paying licensing fees. Recent reports indicate that Verizon and Cisco made payments of $200 million to $400 million for investment and licenses to the Intellectual Ventures portfolio.<ref name=\"Sharma & Clark 2008-09-17\">{{cite web |url=http://webreprints.djreprints.com/2032050299933.pdf |title=Tech Guru Riles the Industry By Seeking Huge Patent Fees |first1=Amol |last1=Sharma |first2=Don |last2=Clark |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=September 17, 2008 |accessdate=June 1, 2009}}</ref> On December 8, 2010, in its 10th year of operations, Intellectual Ventures filed its first lawsuit, accusing [[Check Point]], [[McAfee]], [[NortonLifeLock|Symantec]], [[Trend Micro]], [[Elpida Memory|Elpida]], [[Hynix]], [[Altera]], [[Lattice Semiconductor|Lattice]] and [[Microsemi]] of patent infringement.  In September 2016, the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruled that all the relevant patent claims in the lawsuit were invalid, because \"the patent merely applies a well-known idea using generic computers\".<ref>{{cite web| title=Intellectual Ventures v. Symantec, case 2015-1769 |url=http://www.cafc.uscourts.gov/sites/default/files/opinions-orders/15-1769.Opinion.9-28-2016.1.PDF | author=United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit |date=September 30, 2016 |accessdate=5 October 2016 }}</ref> \n\nThe company has  been accused of hiding behind shell companies for earlier lawsuits,<ref>[http://www.techdirt.com/articles/20100217/1853298215.shtml \"Nathan Myhrvold's Intellectual Ventures Using Over 1,000 Shell Companies To Hide Patent Shakedown\"]</ref> an accusation consistent with the findings of NPR's [[Planet Money]] in July 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/money/2011/07/26/138576167/when-patents-attack |accessdate=2011-07-28 | date=2011-07-22 |title=When Patents Attack}} Alex Blumberg, NPR, July 22, 2011</ref> The episode, which also aired as the ''[[This American Life]]'' episode \"When Patents Attack\",<ref name=\"TALwpa\">[http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/441/when-patents-attack When Patents Attack!]. This American Life. Retrieved on 2013-08-16.</ref> was dedicated to software patents, prominently featuring Intellectual Ventures. It includes sources accusing Intellectual Ventures of pursuing a strategy encouraging [[mutually assured destruction]], including [[Chris Sacca]] calling Myhrvold's argument that Intellectual Ventures is offering protection from lawsuits in a \"[[Pizzo (extortion)|mafia-style shakedown]]\".<ref>{{cite interview |title=When Patents Attack |url=http://www.thisamericanlife.org/play_full.php?play=441 |last=Sacca |first=Chris |subjectlink=Chris Sacca |work=[[This American Life]]  |date= April 5, 1994 |accessdate=March 30, 2007}}  @48:44</ref> However, the firm's internal research, development, and commercialization activities have softened this image. Following a series of research project announcements by Intellectual Ventures, intellectual property columnist Jack Ellis wrote, \"Although licensing is bound to remain a big part of what it does, the more agreements of the kind signed this week IV is involved in, the harder it will be to label as a troll.\"\n\nIntellectual Ventures staff are active in lobbying and testifying in court on United States patent policy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/tipsheets/politico-influence/2014/02/intellectual-ventures-registers-pac-association-trends-honors-leading-lobbyists-fmc-adds-seyfert-steyers-uphill-battle-212543|title=Intellectual Ventures registers PAC \u2014 Association Trends honors leading lobbyists \u2014 FMC adds Seyfert \u2014 Steyer\u2019s uphill battle|website=POLITICO|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.intellectualventures.com/ Intellectual Ventures] \u2013 main website\n* [http://intellectualventureslab.com/ Intellectual Ventures Lab] - Lab web site and blog\n* {{OpenCorp}}\n* This American Life Podcast, [http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/441/when-patents-attack ''When Patents Attack!''], July 22, 2011\n* This American Life Podcast, [http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/496/when-patents-attack-part-two#play ''When Patents Attack... Part Two!''], May 31, 2013\n* The New Yorker, [http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2008/05/12/080512fa_fact_gladwell ''Annals of Innovation: In the Air''], by [[Malcolm Gladwell]], May 12, 2008\n* BusinessWeek Article (cover), [http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/06_27/b3991401.htm ''Microsoft Inside Nathan Myhrvold's Mysterious New Idea Machine''], July 3, 2006\n* CNN Article, [http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2006/07/10/8380798/index.htm?source=yahoo_quote ''Who's afraid of Nathan Myhrvold?''], Jun 26, 2006\n* Boston Globe Article, [http://www.boston.com/business/technology/articles/2006/04/03/inventing_the_future/ ''To boost innovation, firm networks scholars''], April 3, 2006\n* Forbes Article, [https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2005/1114/166.html/ Patent Stalker], November 14, 2005 (Summary)\n* CNET News Article, [http://www.cnet.com/news/microsoft-alums-amass-thousands-of-patents/ ''Microsoft alums amass thousands of patents''], November 3, 2005\n* Defendants Certificate of Interest, [https://web.archive.org/web/20121006095916/http://www.patentlyo.com/financial-interest-in-iv.pdf \"Financial Interest in IV\"], May 16, 2011\n\n[[Category:Patent monetization companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Bellevue, Washington]]\n[[Category:Venture capital firms of the United States]]\n[[Category:Research and development in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Bias|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Intellectual Ventures Management, LLC\n| logo             =Intellectual_Ventures_logo.png\n| type             = [[Privately held company]]\n| predecessor      =\n| successor        =\n| founder          = [[Nathan Myhrvold]]<br>Edward Jung<br>[[Peter Detkin]]<br>Gregory Gorder\n| defunct          =\n| fate             =\n| area_served      =\n| key_people       =\n| industry         = [[Patent monetization]]\n| products         =\n| services         =\n| revenue          =\n| operating_income =\n| net_income       =\n| aum              =\n| assets           =\n| equity           =\n| owner            =\n| num_employees    = 800\n| parent           =\n| divisions        =\n| subsid           =\n| footnotes        =\n| intl             =\n| homepage         = [http://www.intellectualventures.com/ www.intellectualventures.com]\n| foundation       =\n| location_city    = [[Bellevue, Washington]]\n| location_country = [[United States]]\n| location         =\n| locations        = 10\n| market cap       =\n}}\n\n'''Intellectual Ventures''' is an American private company that centers on the development and licensing of intellectual property.  Intellectual Ventures is one of the top-five owners of U.S. patents, as of 2011.<ref>[http://www.patentlyo.com/patent/2011/05/intellectual-ventures-revealing-investors.html \"Intellectual Ventures: Revealing Investors \"], [[Patently-O]] blog, May 18, 2011. Consulted on May 21, 2011.</ref> {{Verify source|date=June 2017}} Its business model has a focus on buying patents and aggregating them into a large [[patent portfolio]] and licensing these patents to third parties. The company has been described as the country's largest and most notorious [[patent trolling]] company,<ref>{{cite web |title=RPX and the complicated business of stockpiling patents for good, not evil |url=https://pando.com/2013/09/09/rpx-and-the-complicated-business-of-stockpiling-patents-for-good-not-evil/ |website=Pando |language=en-gb |date=9 September 2013}}</ref> the ultimate [[patent troll]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Robertson |first1=Adi |title=The ultimate patent troll is going to trial against Google and Motorola |url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/2/4/5375304/intellectual-ventures-goes-to-trial-against-google-and-motorola |website=The Verge |date=4 February 2014}}</ref>, and the most hated company in tech.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kerstetter |first1=Jim |title=Inside Intellectual Ventures, the most hated company in tech |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/inside-intellectual-ventures-the-most-hated-company-in-tech/ |website=CNET |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the firm launched a prototyping and research laboratory,  Intellectual Ventures Lab''','''<ref>[http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2009266390_intvent70.html \"Bellevue lab is an inventor's real dream\"] by Brier Dudley, The Seattle Times -  27 May 2009<!--accessed June 1, 2009--></ref> which attracted media controversy when the book ''[[SuperFreakonomics]]'' described its ideas for [[Climate change mitigation|reducing global climate change]]. The firm also collaborates on humanitarian projects through its Global Good program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.intellectualventures.com/globalgood/|title=Global Good|website=www.intellectualventures.com|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nIn 2000, Intellectual Ventures was founded as a private partnership by [[Nathan Myhrvold]] and Edward Jung of [[Microsoft]], later joined by co-founders [[Peter Detkin]] of [[Intel]], and Gregory Gorder of [[Perkins Coie]].  The Intellectual Ventures Management Company is owned 40% [[Nathan Myhrvold]], 20% [[Peter Detkin]], 20% Gregory Gorder and 20% Edward Jung. They reportedly have raised over $5.5 billion from many large companies including [[Microsoft]], [[Intel]], [[Sony]], [[Nokia]], [[Apple Computer|Apple]], [[Google]], [[Yahoo]], [[American Express]], [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]], [[SAP AG|SAP]], [[Nvidia]], and [[eBay]], plus investment firms such as [[Stanford]], [[Hewlett Foundation]], [[Mayo Clinic]], and [[Charles River Ventures]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patentlyo.com/financial-interest-in-iv.pdf|title=Defendants Certificate of Interest|date=2011-05-16|publisher=US District Court, N. California|access-date=2013-07-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006095916/http://www.patentlyo.com/financial-interest-in-iv.pdf|archive-date=2012-10-06|url-status=dead}}</ref> In December 2013, the firm released a list of approximately 33,000 of the nearly 40,000 assets in their monetization program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://patents.intven.com/finder|title=Intellectual Ventures Find a Patent|date=2013-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richardsonoliver.com/news/2014/6/4/whats-inside-ivs-patent-portfolio|title=What's Inside IV's Patent Portfolio|location=London| work=[[IAM Magazine]]|first=Kent|last=Richardson|date=2014-06-14}} Issue 66. July/August 2014</ref> Licenses to patents are obtained through investment and [[royalties]].<ref>[http://www.pcworld.com/article/id,132174-c,opensource/article.html \"Ubuntu: Microsoft is Patent Pal\"] by Matthew Broersma, PCWorld - 23 May 2007</ref> In March 2009, the firm announced expansion into China, India, Japan, Korea and Singapore to build partnerships with  scientists and institutions in Asia.\n<!--\nNotable then uncomment?: In November 2015, Intellectual Ventures opened a new lab<ref>http://www.intellectualventures.com/insights/archives/intellectual-ventures-opens-new-laboratory</ref> -->\n\n==Investment funds==\nThe company operates three primary investment funds:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.intellectualventures.com/Libraries/General/Investing_in_Invention_Graphical_Representation.sflb.ashx |title=Investing in Invention |accessdate=2010-12-26 |website=Intellectual Ventures |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100630210845/http://www.intellectualventures.com/Libraries/General/Investing_in_Invention_Graphical_Representation.sflb.ashx |archivedate=2010-06-30 }}</ref>\n\n* Invention Investment Fund (IIF), purchasing existing inventions and licensing them\n* Invention Development Fund (IDF), partnering chiefly with research institutions to file descriptions of new inventions\n* Investment Science Fund (ISF), focused on internally developed inventions\n\n==Intellectual Ventures Lab==\nIn 2009, Intellectual Ventures launched a prototyping and research laboratory,  Intellectual Ventures Lab, hiring  scientists to imagine inventions which could exist but do not yet exist, and then filing descriptions of these inventions with the US Patent Office.  Notable participants  include [[Robert Langer]] of MIT, [[Leroy Hood]] of the [[Institute for Systems Biology]], Ed Harlow of Harvard Medical School, [[Bran Ferren]] and [[Danny Hillis]] of [[Applied Minds]], and Sir [[John Pendry]] of Imperial College.{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}}  The ''[[Sunday Times]]'' reported that the company applies for about 450 patents per year, in areas from vaccine research to optical computing and, as of May 2010, 91 of the applications had been approved.<ref name=\"Harris\">{{cite news |url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/entrepreneur/article7127608.ece\n|title=Green Pioneers: Godfather of nutty inventions\n| location=London\n| work=[[The Times]]\n| first=Mark\n| last=Harris\n| date=May 16, 2010\n}} Mark Harris, The Sunday Times, May 16, 2010</ref> Internally developed inventions include a [[Traveling wave reactor|safer nuclear reactor design]] (which won the MIT Technology Review Top 10 Emerging Technologies in 2009) that can use uranium waste as fuel or thorium which is plentiful and poses no proliferation risk,<ref>[http://beta.technologyreview.com/read_article.aspx?ch=specialsections&sc=tr10&id=22114 \"TR10: Traveling-Wave Reactor\"]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} by Matt Wald, Technology Review - March/April 2009</ref> a mosquito-targeting laser,<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/science/article5908535.ece \"Mosquito laser gun offers new hope on malaria\"] by Tony Allen-Mills - 15 March 2009</ref> and a series of computer models of infectious disease.<ref>[http://www.hertzfoundation.org/lib/literature/Hertz_Spring09_V11.pdf \"Mathematics, Mosquitoes, and Malaria\"] by Philip Eckhoff, Hertz Foundation Biennial Symposium - Spring 2009, Volume 11</ref>\n\nTheir efforts to promote a method to reverse or reduce the effects of global climate change by artificially recreating the conditions from the aftermath of a volcanic eruption gained media coverage following the release of the book ''SuperFreakonomics'', whosechapter about [[global warming]] proposes that the global climate can be regulated by [[geo-engineering]] of a [[stratoshield]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://intellectualventureslab.com/?tag=stratoshield|title=Introducing the Stratoshield|date=2009-10-21|publisher=Intellectual Ventures}}</ref> based upon patented technology from the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.techflash.com/seattle/2009/10/video_nathan_myhrvold_explains_how_to_save_the_world.html|title=Stratoshield: Nathan Myhrvold explains how to save the planet|author=Todd Bishop|publisher=TechFlash|date=2009-10-14}}</ref> The chapter has been criticized by some economists and climate science experts who say it contains numerous misleading statements and discredited arguments, including this presentation of geoengineering as a replacement for CO<sub>2</sub> emissions reduction.  Among the critics are [[Paul Krugman]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://krugman.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/10/17/superfreakonomics-on-climate-part-1/ |title=SuperFreakonomics on climate, part 1 |author=Paul Krugman |date=2009-10-17 |quote=\"they grossly misrepresent other peoples\u2019 research, in both climate science and economics\" | work=The New York Times}}</ref> [[J. Bradford DeLong|Brad DeLong]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://delong.typepad.com/sdj/2009/10/yet-more-superfreakonomics-blogging-yes-i-know-i-know.html |title=Yet More SuperFreakonomics Blogging. |author=Brad DeLong |date=2009-10-19 |work=Grasping Reality with All Eight Tentacles|quote=Levitt and Dubner today appear to no longer be thinking like economists}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2009/oct/19/superfreakonomics-geoengineering-wrong|title=Why SuperFreakonomics' authors are wrong on geo-engineering|date=2009-10-19|quote=Many commentators have already pointed out dozens of misquotes, misrepresentations and mistakes in the 'Global Cooling' chapter | location=London | work=The Guardian}}</ref> and ''[[The Economist]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/world/international/displaystory.cfm?story_id=14738383|title=Freaking out: The controversy over SuperFreakonomics |date=2009-10-27|publisher=The Economist|accessdate=2009-11-06}}</ref>  Elizabeth Kolbert, a science writer for ''[[The New Yorker]]'' who has written extensively on global warming, contends that \"just about everything they [Levitt and Dubner] have to say on the topic is, factually speaking, wrong.\"<ref>\"{{cite news |author=Kolbert, Elizabeth |title=Hosed: Is there a quick fix for the climate?\" [rev. of Levitt and Dubner's SuperFreakonomics and Al Gore's Our Choice] |url=http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/books/2009/11/16/091116crbo_books_kolbert |publisher=New Yorker |date=November 16, 2009  }}</ref> In response, Levitt and Dubner have stated on their ''Freakonomics'' blog that global warming is [[Human impact on the environment|man-made]] and an important issue. They warn against claims of an inevitable doomsday; instead they look to raise awareness of less traditional or popular, methods to tackle the potential problem of global warming.<ref>{{Cite news|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|url=http://freakonomics.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/10/17/the-rumors-of-our-global-warming-denial-are-greatly-exaggerated/|title=The Rumors of Our Global-Warming Denial Are Greatly Exaggerated|date=2009-10-17|quote=\"... we believe that rising global temperatures are a man-made phenomenon and that global warming is an important issue to solve. Where we differ from the critics is in our view of the most effective solutions to this problem.\" and \"The real purpose of the chapter is figuring out how to cool the Earth if indeed it becomes catastrophically warmer... if we weren\u2019t convinced that global warming was worth worrying about, we wouldn\u2019t have written a chapter about proposed solutions. | first=Steven D. | last=Levitt}}</ref>\n\n[[Lowell Wood]], an \"inventor in residence\" at Intellectual Ventures, became the most-patented inventor in US history in 2015, breaking the record held by Thomas Edison for over 80 years.\n\n== Global Good ==\nGlobal Good is collaboration between the firm and the Gates Foundation to develop  solutions for pressing problems in the developing world. It's technologies include:\n\nArktek, a passive vaccine storage device that allows [[vaccine]]s to be transported to parts of the world that lack reliable refrigeration. It uses a small amount of ice for cooling and requires no external power supply, relying on extraordinary insulation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2015/11/23/455580587/how-do-you-keep-vaccines-cool-try-spacecraft-insulation|title=How Do You Keep Vaccines Cool? Try Spacecraft Insulation|website=NPR.org|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref> The device has been used to transport vaccines around the world, and  Myhrvold believes the device may be useful for transporting organs. The firm produced a modified version of the Arktek to transport newly developed [[Ebola virus disease|Ebola]] vaccines to [[Sierra Leone]] and [[Guinea]] during the [[West African Ebola virus epidemic|2014 Ebola outbreak]] at the required much colder temperature.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/01/world/africa/experimental-ebola-vaccine-in-guinea-shows-promise-report-says.html|title=Experimental Ebola Vaccine Tested in Guinea Shows Promise, Report Says|last=Fink|first=Sheri|date=2015-07-31|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref>\n\nThe Photonic Fence is a device  to identify and kill mosquitos with lasers to prevent malaria, suggested by  Lowell Wood, an company researcher.   The device uses a non-lethal laser to track insects and monitor their wing-beat frequency. If it detects a female mosquito, the device fires a kill laser. It has an effective range of 100 feet and can purportedly kill up to 100 mosquitoes per second. The device has not yet been mass-produced,.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.geekwire.com/2015/intellectual-ventures-laser-mosquito-zapper-one-step-closer-to-commercialization/|title=Intellectual Ventures\u2019 laser mosquito zapper lands key licensing deal|date=2015-03-03|website=GeekWire|language=en-US|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref>\n\nThe Autoscope uses artificial intelligence to diagnose [[malaria]]. The device has been field-tested in Thailand and reportedly outperformed the average human diagnostician. It too is not yet scheduled for mass-production.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/600779/artificial-intelligence-offers-a-better-way-to-diagnose-malaria/|title=Artificial Intelligence Offers a Better Way to Diagnose Malaria|website=MIT Technology Review|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref>\n\nMazzi is a milk jug designed for farmers in the developing world. The firm partnered with [[Heifer International]] to design the jug, which is cheap, sturdy, and easy to clean with features a funnel that results in decreased spillage.\n\n==Companies created==\nIntellectual Ventures has created a number of independent companies to bring its discoveries to mass market. Examples include [[Kymeta]], a satellite technology company,<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.kymetacorp.com/history/|title = Kymeta Company History|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151009170150/https://www.kymetacorp.com/history/|archive-date = 2015-10-09|url-status = dead}}</ref> [[TerraPower]], which seeks to improve nuclear power,<ref>{{Cite web|title = About TerraPower {{!}} TerraPower|url = http://terrapower.com/pages/about|website = terrapower.com|accessdate = 2015-11-01}}</ref> Evolv, which applies metamaterials to imaging,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.intellectualventures.com/inventions-patents/spinouts-programs/evolv/|title=Evolv|website=www.intellectualventures.com|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref> and [[Echodyne]], a [[metamaterial]]s-based radar communications company.<ref>{{Cite web|title = About Us {{!}} Echodyne|url = http://echodyne.com/about-us/|website = echodyne.com|accessdate = 2015-11-01}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n{{Main|Patent trolling}}\n\nPublicly, Intellectual Ventures states that a major goal is to assist small inventors against corporations. In practice, the vast majority of IV's revenue comes from buying patents, aggregating these patents into a single portfolio spanning many disparate technologies and [[Tying (commerce)|tying]] these patents together for license to other companies under the threat of litigation, or filing lawsuits for infringement of patents, a controversial practice referred to as \"patent trolling.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Here's Why Software Patents Are in Peril After the Intellectual Ventures Ruling |work=Fortune Magazine |url=http://fortune.com/2016/10/03/software-patents/ |first=Jeff John |last=Roberts |date=October 3, 2016 |accessdate=5 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIntellectual Ventures' purchased patents have largely been kept secret, though press releases with [[Telcordia]] and [[Transmeta]] indicated some or all of their patent portfolios were sold to the company. It reports that its purchasing activity as of spring 2010 has sent $350 million to individual inventors, and $848 million to small and medium size enterprises as well as returning \"approximately $1 billion\" to investors before filing any lawsuits, but IV's assistance to individual inventors has been contested.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/441/when-patents-attack|title=When Patents Attack! {{!}} This American Life|website=This American Life|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref> Investigative journalism suggests that the company makes most of its income from lawsuits and licensing of already-existing inventions, rather than from its own innovation. Intellectual Ventures has been described as a \"patent troll\" by Shane Robison,<ref>{{cite journal |first=Nicholas |last=Varchaver |date=July 10, 2006 |title=Who's afraid of Nathan Myhrvold? |journal=Fortune |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2006/07/10/8380798/index.htm}}</ref> CTO of [[Hewlett Packard]] and others, allegedly accumulating patents not in order to develop products around them but with the goal to pressure large companies into paying licensing fees. Recent reports indicate that Verizon and Cisco made payments of $200 million to $400 million for investment and licenses to the Intellectual Ventures portfolio.<ref name=\"Sharma & Clark 2008-09-17\">{{cite web |url=http://webreprints.djreprints.com/2032050299933.pdf |title=Tech Guru Riles the Industry By Seeking Huge Patent Fees |first1=Amol |last1=Sharma |first2=Don |last2=Clark |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=September 17, 2008 |accessdate=June 1, 2009}}</ref> On December 8, 2010, in its 10th year of operations, Intellectual Ventures filed its first lawsuit, accusing [[Check Point]], [[McAfee]], [[NortonLifeLock|Symantec]], [[Trend Micro]], [[Elpida Memory|Elpida]], [[Hynix]], [[Altera]], [[Lattice Semiconductor|Lattice]] and [[Microsemi]] of patent infringement.  In September 2016, the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruled that all the relevant patent claims in the lawsuit were invalid, because \"the patent merely applies a well-known idea using generic computers\".<ref>{{cite web| title=Intellectual Ventures v. Symantec, case 2015-1769 |url=http://www.cafc.uscourts.gov/sites/default/files/opinions-orders/15-1769.Opinion.9-28-2016.1.PDF | author=United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit |date=September 30, 2016 |accessdate=5 October 2016 }}</ref> \n\nThe company has  been accused of hiding behind shell companies for earlier lawsuits,<ref>[http://www.techdirt.com/articles/20100217/1853298215.shtml \"Nathan Myhrvold's Intellectual Ventures Using Over 1,000 Shell Companies To Hide Patent Shakedown\"]</ref> an accusation consistent with the findings of NPR's [[Planet Money]] in July 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/money/2011/07/26/138576167/when-patents-attack |accessdate=2011-07-28 | date=2011-07-22 |title=When Patents Attack}} Alex Blumberg, NPR, July 22, 2011</ref> The episode, which also aired as the ''[[This American Life]]'' episode \"When Patents Attack\",<ref name=\"TALwpa\">[http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/441/when-patents-attack When Patents Attack!]. This American Life. Retrieved on 2013-08-16.</ref> was dedicated to software patents, prominently featuring Intellectual Ventures. It includes sources accusing Intellectual Ventures of pursuing a strategy encouraging [[mutually assured destruction]], including [[Chris Sacca]] calling Myhrvold's argument that Intellectual Ventures is offering protection from lawsuits in a \"[[Pizzo (extortion)|mafia-style shakedown]]\".<ref>{{cite interview |title=When Patents Attack |url=http://www.thisamericanlife.org/play_full.php?play=441 |last=Sacca |first=Chris |subjectlink=Chris Sacca |work=[[This American Life]]  |date= April 5, 1994 |accessdate=March 30, 2007}}  @48:44</ref> However, the firm's internal research, development, and commercialization activities have softened this image. Following a series of research project announcements by Intellectual Ventures, intellectual property columnist Jack Ellis wrote, \"Although licensing is bound to remain a big part of what it does, the more agreements of the kind signed this week IV is involved in, the harder it will be to label as a troll.\"\n\nIntellectual Ventures staff are active in lobbying and testifying in court on United States patent policy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/tipsheets/politico-influence/2014/02/intellectual-ventures-registers-pac-association-trends-honors-leading-lobbyists-fmc-adds-seyfert-steyers-uphill-battle-212543|title=Intellectual Ventures registers PAC \u2014 Association Trends honors leading lobbyists \u2014 FMC adds Seyfert \u2014 Steyer\u2019s uphill battle|website=POLITICO|access-date=2016-06-16}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.intellectualventures.com/ Intellectual Ventures] \u2013 main website\n* [http://intellectualventureslab.com/ Intellectual Ventures Lab] - Lab web site and blog\n* {{OpenCorp}}\n* This American Life Podcast, [http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/441/when-patents-attack ''When Patents Attack!''], July 22, 2011\n* This American Life Podcast, [http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/496/when-patents-attack-part-two#play ''When Patents Attack... Part Two!''], May 31, 2013\n* The New Yorker, [http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2008/05/12/080512fa_fact_gladwell ''Annals of Innovation: In the Air''], by [[Malcolm Gladwell]], May 12, 2008\n* BusinessWeek Article (cover), [http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/06_27/b3991401.htm ''Microsoft Inside Nathan Myhrvold's Mysterious New Idea Machine''], July 3, 2006\n* CNN Article, [http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2006/07/10/8380798/index.htm?source=yahoo_quote ''Who's afraid of Nathan Myhrvold?''], Jun 26, 2006\n* Boston Globe Article, [http://www.boston.com/business/technology/articles/2006/04/03/inventing_the_future/ ''To boost innovation, firm networks scholars''], April 3, 2006\n* Forbes Article, [https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2005/1114/166.html/ Patent Stalker], November 14, 2005 (Summary)\n* CNET News Article, [http://www.cnet.com/news/microsoft-alums-amass-thousands-of-patents/ ''Microsoft alums amass thousands of patents''], November 3, 2005\n* Defendants Certificate of Interest, [https://web.archive.org/web/20121006095916/http://www.patentlyo.com/financial-interest-in-iv.pdf \"Financial Interest in IV\"], May 16, 2011\n\n[[Category:Patent monetization companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Bellevue, Washington]]\n[[Category:Venture capital firms of the United States]]\n[[Category:Research and development in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Tengri 0", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIntellectual Ventures Lab", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intellectual_Ventures"}
{"title_page": "Fantastica Mania 2011", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese/Mexican professional wrestling show series}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestling event\n|name       = ''Fantastica Mania'' 2011\n|image      = FantasticaMania2.jpg\n|caption    = Official poster for the January 23rd Fantastica Mania\n|promotion  = [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]] / [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]]\n|date       = {{dts|2011|1|22}}<br>{{dts|2011|1|23}}\n|date_aired =\n|attendance = 1,800 (January 22)<br>2,005 (January 23)\n|venue      = [[Korakuen Hall]]\n|city       = [[Tokyo, Japan]]\n|liveevent=Y\n|lastevent=First\n|nextevent=[[Fantastica Mania 2012|2012]]\n|event=[[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]] event\n|lastevent2=[[CMLL Reyes del Aire#CMLL Reyes del Aire 2011|Reyes del Aire]]\n|nextevent2=[[Peque\u00f1o Reyes del Aire#Peque\u00f1os Reyes del Aire (2011)|Peque\u00f1os Reyes del Aire]]\n|event2=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] event\n|lastevent3=[[Wrestle Kingdom V in Tokyo Dome]]\n|nextevent3=[[The New Beginning (2011)|The New Beginning]]\n}}\n'''''Fantastica Mania'' 2011''' was the name of two [[professional wrestling]] major shows produced that took place on January 22 and January 23, 2011 in [[Korakuen Hall]] in [[Tokyo, Japan]]. The event was the first ever co-promoted events between Japanese [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] (NJPW) and the Mexican [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]] (CMLL) and features matches with wrestlers from both promotions and both NJPW and CMLL championships being defended.\n\nOn the first night NJPW wrestler [[Ryusuke Taguchi]] defeated [[M\u00e1scara Dorada]] to win the [[CMLL World Welterweight Championship]], marking the first time that a NJPW wrestler had won that particular title. Night one also saw NJPW representatives successfully defend the [[CMLL World Middleweight Championship]] and the [[IWGP Tag Team Championship]] against CMLL challengers. On night two [[La Sombra (wrestler)|La Sombra]], M\u00e1scara Dorada and [[La Mascara (wrestler)|La Mascara]]  successfully defended the [[CMLL World Trios Championship]] on the undercard while [[Apollo 55]] ([[Prince Devitt]] and [[Ryusuke Taguchi]]) defeated [[Golden\u2606Lovers]] ([[Kota Ibushi]] and [[Kenny Omega]]) bringing the [[IWGP Junior Heavyweight Tag Team Championship]] back to the promotion after being held by the [[Dramatic Dream Team|DDT]] team since October 2010. Also on night two [[Tiger Mask IV|Tiger Mask]] defeated longtime rival [[Tomohiro Ishii]] in a ''[[Lucha de Apuestas]]'', forcing Ishii to have his hair shaved off.\n\n==Background==\nEach of the events featured six [[professional wrestling matches]], some with different wrestlers involved in pre-existing [[script (recorded media)|scripted]] feuds or [[narrative thread|storylines]] while other matches were the first time some wrestlers faced off. The Fantastica Mania events was the result of several years of co-operation between [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] and [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]], which had seen both companies exchange wrestlers for various events.<ref name=SL398>{{cite news | author= Flores, Manuel | title= NJPW CMLL Presents Fantasticamania 2011 | work=[[Super Luchas]] | pages= 3\u20137 | id = Issue 398 | date= January 24, 2011 | accessdate= January 31, 2011 | url= http://superluchas.net/2011/01/23/revista-super-luchas-398-desde-el-lunes-24-de-enero-reporte-total-cmll-vs-njpw-en-tokyo-japon/ | publisher= CAMSAN Impresores, S.A. de C.V. | location= [[Mexico City|Mexico City, Mexico]] | language=Spanish}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Results==\n===January 22===\n{{Pro Wrestling results table \n|results=<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM1>{{cite web | url= http://superluchas.com/resultados-fantasticamania-cmllnjpw-en-japon-los-mexicanos-perdieron-todos-los-duelos-por-campeonatos/ | title= Resultados \"Fantasticaman\u00eda\" \u2013 CMLL/NJPW en Jap\u00f3n \u2013 Los mexicanos perdieron todos los duelos por campeonatos | author= Flores, Manuel | date= January 22, 2011 | accessdate= January 31, 2011 | publisher=[[Super Luchas]]| language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=PuroFM1>{{cite web | url= http://www.puroresufan.com/njpw/?p=2518 | title= Results: New Japan x CMLL, 1/22/11 | date= January 22, 2011 | accessdate= January 31, 2011 | publisher= Puroresufan}}</ref>\n\n|match1=[[Taichi Ishikari|Taichi]] defeated [[Maximo (wrestler)|M\u00e1ximo]]\n|stip1=[[Professional wrestling match types#Variations of singles matches|Singles match]]\n|time1=12:39\n\n|match2=[[Ryusuke Taguchi]] defeated [[M\u00e1scara Dorada]] (c) \u2013 two falls to one\n|stip2=[[Professional wrestling match types#Series variations|Two out of three falls match]] for the [[CMLL World Welterweight Championship]]<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM1/><ref name=PuroFM1/>\n|time2=11:20\n\n|match3=[[Jyushin Thunder Liger]] (c) defeated [[La Sombra (wrestler)|La Sombra]] \u2013 two falls to one\n|stip3=Two out of three falls match for the [[CMLL World Middleweight Championship]]<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM1/><ref name=PuroFM1/>\n|time3=16:28\n\n|match4=''[[Bad Intentions (professional wrestling)|Bad Intentions]]'' ([[Karl Anderson]] and [[Giant Bernard]]) (c) defeated [[Atlantis (wrestler)|Atlantis]] and [[Shigeo Okumura|Okumura]]\n|stip4=[[Professional wrestling tag team match types|Tag Team match]] for the [[IWGP Tag Team Championship]]<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM1/><ref name=PuroFM1/>\n|time4=13:06\n\n|match5=[[Drag\u00f3n Rojo, Jr.]] and [[Tomohiro Ishii]] defeated [[La Mascara (wrestler)|La M\u00e1scara]] and [[Tiger Mask IV|Tiger Mask]]\n|stip5=Tag Team match<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM1/><ref name=PuroFM1/>\n|time5=10:06\n\n|match6=[[Shinsuke Nakamura]], [[Tetsuya Naito]] and [[Averno (wrestler)|Averno]] defeated [[Hiroshi Tanahashi]], [[Prince Devitt]] and [[M\u00edstico]]\n|stip6=\"[[Victor Mar Manuel|Black Cat]] Memorial Match\" [[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Multiple man teamed matches|Six-man tag team match]]<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM1/><ref name=PuroFM1/>\n|time6=14:33\n\n}}\n\n===January 23===\n{{Pro Wrestling results table \n|results=<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM2>{{cite web | url= http://superluchas.com/resultados-njpw-presents-cmll-fantastica-mania-2011-23-de-enero/ | title= Resultados NJPW PRESENTS CMLL FANTASTICA MANIA 2011, 23 de enero. | author= Zayfreb| date= January 23, 2011 | accessdate= January 31, 2011 | publisher=[[Super Luchas]]| language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=PuroFM2>{{cite web | url= http://www.puroresufan.com/njpw/?p=2525 | title= Results: New Japan x CMLL, 1/23/11 | date= January 23, 2011 | accessdate= January 31, 2011 | publisher= Puroresufan}}</ref>\n\n|match1=[[The World Class Tag Team|Jado and Gedo]] defeated [[Danshoku Dino]] and [[Maximo (wrestler)|M\u00e1ximo]]\n|stip1=[[Professional wrestling tag team match types|Tag Team match]]\n|time1=10:39\n\n|match2=''[[Bad Intentions (professional wrestling)|Bad Intentions]]'' ([[Karl Anderson]] and [[Giant Bernard]]) and [[Jyushin Thunder Liger]] defeated [[Atlantis (wrestler)|Atlantis]], [[Drag\u00f3n Rojo, Jr.]] and [[Taichi Ishikari|Taichi]]\n|stip2=[[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Multiple man teamed matches|Six-man tag team match]]<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM2/><ref name=PuroFM2/>\n|time2=11:08\n\n|match3=''La Generacion Dorada'' ([[La Sombra (wrestler)|La Sombra]], [[M\u00e1scara Dorada]] and [[La Mascara (wrestler)|La M\u00e1scara]]) (c) defeated ''[[La Ola Amarillo]]'' ([[Yujiro Takahashi]], [[Tetsuya Naito]] and [[Shigeo Okumura|Okumura]])\n|stip3=[[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Trios rules (Relevos Australianos)|Two out of three falls six-man tag team match]] for the [[CMLL World Trios Championship]]<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM2/><ref name=PuroFM2/>\n|time3=24:27\n\n|match4=[[Tiger Mask IV|Tiger Mask]] defeated [[Tomohiro Ishii]]\n|stip4=''[[Lucha de Apuestas]]'', mask vs. hair match<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM2/><ref name=PuroFM2/>\n|time4=12:16\n\n|match5=[[M\u00edstico]] defeated [[Averno (wrestler)|Averno]] \u2013 two falls to one\n|stip5=[[Professional wrestling match types#Series variations|Two out of three falls match]]<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM2/><ref name=PuroFM2/>\n|time5=16:50\n\n|match6=[[Apollo 55]] ([[Prince Devitt]] and [[Ryusuke Taguchi]]) defeated [[Golden\u2606Lovers]] ([[Kota Ibushi]] and [[Kenny Omega]]) (c)\n|stip6=Tag Team match for the [[IWGP Junior Heavyweight Tag Team Championship]]<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM2/><ref name=PuroFM2/>\n|time6=16:32\n\n}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[2011 in professional wrestling]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{CMLLShows|Fantastica Mania}}\n{{New Japan Pro Wrestling events|Fantastica Mania}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Fantastica Mania'' 2011}}\n\n[[Category:2011 in professional wrestling]]\n[[Category:Fantastica Mania|2011]]\n[[Category:2011 in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:January 2011 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling in Tokyo]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Japanese/Mexican professional wrestling show series}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestling event\n|name       = ''Fantastica Mania'' 2011\n|image      = FantasticaMania2.jpg\n|caption    = Official poster for the January 23rd Fantastica Mania\n|promotion  = [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]] / [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]]\n|date       = {{dts|2011|1|22}}<br>{{dts|2011|1|23}}\n|date_aired =\n|attendance = 1,800 (January 22)<br>2,005 (January 23)\n|venue      = [[Korakuen Hall]]\n|city       = [[Tokyo, Japan]]\n|liveevent=Y\n|lastevent=First\n|nextevent=[[Fantastica Mania 2012|2012]]\n|event=[[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]] event\n|lastevent2=[[CMLL Reyes del Aire#CMLL Reyes del Aire 2011|Reyes del Aire]]\n|nextevent2=[[Peque\u00f1o Reyes del Aire#Peque\u00f1os Reyes del Aire (2011)|Peque\u00f1os Reyes del Aire]]\n|event2=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] event\n|lastevent3=[[Wrestle Kingdom V in Tokyo Dome]]\n|nextevent3=[[The New Beginning (2011)|The New Beginning]]\n}}\n'''''Fantastica Mania'' 2011''' was the name of two [[professional wrestling]] major shows produced that took place on January 22 and January 23, 2011 in [[Korakuen Hall]] in [[Tokyo, Japan]]. The event was the first ever co-promoted events between Japanese [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] (NJPW) and the Mexican [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]] (CMLL) and features matches with wrestlers from both promotions and both NJPW and CMLL championships being defended.\n\nOn the first night NJPW wrestler [[Ryusuke Taguchi]] defeated [[M\u00e1scara Dorada]] to win the [[CMLL World Welterweight Championship]], marking the first time that a NJPW wrestler had won that particular title. Night one also saw NJPW representatives successfully defend the [[CMLL World Middleweight Championship]] and the [[IWGP Tag Team Championship]] against CMLL challengers. On night two [[La Sombra (wrestler)|La Sombra]], M\u00e1scara Dorada and [[La Mascara (wrestler)|La Mascara]]  successfully defended the [[CMLL World Trios Championship]] on the undercard while [[Apollo 55]] ([[Prince Devitt]] and [[Ryusuke Taguchi]]) defeated [[Golden\u2606Lovers]] ([[Kota Ibushi]] and [[Kenny Omega]]) bringing the [[IWGP Junior Heavyweight Tag Team Championship]] back to the promotion after being held by the [[Dramatic Dream Team|DDT]] team since October 2010. Also on night two [[Tiger Mask IV|Tiger Mask]] defeated longtime rival [[Tomohiro Ishii]] in a ''[[Lucha de Apuestas]]'', forcing Ishii to have his hair shaved off.\n\n==Background==\nEach of the events featured six [[professional wrestling matches]], some with different wrestlers involved in pre-existing [[script (recorded media)|scripted]] feuds or [[narrative thread|storylines]] while other matches were the first time some wrestlers faced off. The Fantastica Mania events was the result of several years of co-operation between [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] and [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]], which had seen both companies exchange wrestlers for various events.<ref name=SL398>{{cite news | author= Flores, Manuel | title= NJPW CMLL Presents Fantasticamania 2011 | work=[[Super Luchas]] | pages= 3\u20137 | id = Issue 398 | date= January 24, 2011 | accessdate= January 31, 2011 | url= http://superluchas.net/2011/01/23/revista-super-luchas-398-desde-el-lunes-24-de-enero-reporte-total-cmll-vs-njpw-en-tokyo-japon/ | publisher= CAMSAN Impresores, S.A. de C.V. | location= [[Mexico City|Mexico City, Mexico]] | language=Spanish}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Results==\n===January 22===\n{{Pro Wrestling results table \n|results=<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM1>{{cite web | url= http://superluchas.com/resultados-fantasticamania-cmllnjpw-en-japon-los-mexicanos-perdieron-todos-los-duelos-por-campeonatos/ | title= Resultados \"Fantasticaman\u00eda\" \u2013 CMLL/NJPW en Jap\u00f3n \u2013 Los mexicanos perdieron todos los duelos por campeonatos | author= Flores, Manuel | date= January 22, 2011 | accessdate= January 31, 2011 | publisher=[[Super Luchas]]| language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=PuroFM1>{{cite web | url= http://www.puroresufan.com/njpw/?p=2518 | title= Results: New Japan x CMLL, 1/22/11 | date= January 22, 2011 | accessdate= January 31, 2011 | publisher= Puroresufan}}</ref>\n\n|match1=[[Taichi Ishikari|Taichi]] defeated [[Maximo (wrestler)|M\u00e1ximo]]\n|stip1=[[Professional wrestling match types#Variations of singles matches|Singles match]]\n|time1=12:39\n\n|match2=[[Ryusuke Taguchi]] defeated [[M\u00e1scara Dorada]] (c) \u2013 two falls to one\n|stip2=[[Professional wrestling match types#Series variations|Two out of three falls match]] for the [[CMLL World Welterweight Championship]]<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM1/><ref name=PuroFM1/>\n|time2=11:20\n\n|match3=[[Jyushin Thunder Liger]] (c) defeated [[La Sombra (wrestler)|La Sombra]] \u2013 two falls to one\n|stip3=Two out of three falls match for the [[CMLL World Middleweight Championship]]<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM1/><ref name=PuroFM1/>\n|time3=16:28\n\n|match4=''[[Bad Intentions (professional wrestling)|Bad Intentions]]'' ([[Karl Anderson]] and [[Giant Bernard]]) (c) defeated [[Atlantis (wrestler)|Atlantis]] and [[Shigeo Okumura|Okumura]]\n|stip4=[[Professional wrestling tag team match types|Tag Team match]] for the [[IWGP Tag Team Championship]]<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM1/><ref name=PuroFM1/>\n|time4=13:06\n\n|match5=[[Drag\u00f3n Rojo, Jr.]] and [[Tomohiro Ishii]] defeated [[La Mascara (wrestler)|La M\u00e1scara]] and [[Tiger Mask IV|Tiger Mask]]\n|stip5=Tag Team match<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM1/><ref name=PuroFM1/>\n|time5=10:06\n\n|match6=[[Shinsuke Nakamura]], [[Tetsuya Naito]] and [[Averno (wrestler)|Averno]] defeated [[Hiroshi Tanahashi]], [[Prince Devitt]] and [[M\u00edstico]]\n|stip6=\"[[Victor Mar Manuel|Black Cat]] Memorial Match\" [[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Multiple man teamed matches|Six-man tag team match]]<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM1/><ref name=PuroFM1/>\n|time6=14:33\n\n}}\n\n===January 23===\n{{Pro Wrestling results table \n|results=<ref name=SL398/><ref name=LuchaFM2>{{cite web | url= http://superluchas.com/resultados-njpw-presents-cmll-fantastica-mania-2011-23-de-enero/ | title= Resultados NJPW PRESENTS CMLL FANTASTICA MANIA 2011, 23 de enero. | author= Zayfreb| date= January 23, 2011 | accessdate= January 31, 2011 | publisher=[[Super Luchas]]| language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=PuroFM2>{{cite web | url= http://www.puroresufan.com/njpw/?p=2525 | title= Results: New Japan x CMLL, 1/23/11 | date= January 23, 2011 | accessdate= January 31, 2011 | publisher= Puroresufan}}</ref>\n\n|match1=[[The World Class Tag Team|Jado and Gedo]] defeated [[Danshoku Dino]] and [[Maximo (wrestler)|M\u00e1ximo]]\n|stip1=[[Professional wrestling tag team match types|Tag Team match]]\n|time1=10:39\n\n|match2=''[[Bad Intentions (professional wrestling)|Bad Intentions]]'' ([[Karl Anderson]] and [[Giant Bernard]]) and [[Jyushin Thunder Liger]] defeated [[Atlantis (wrestler)|Atlantis]], [[Drag\u00f3n Rojo, Jr.]] and [[Taichi Ishikari|Taichi]]\n|stip2